'''Olivier Ciappa''' (born 17 March 1979 in [[Marseille]]) is a French photographer and film director. 
He is a director of short films, a director of musicals for the theater, illustrator of books for children, producer and director of documentaries, journalist of cinema, photographer also creator of stamps.

Olivier Ciappa is in particular the director of movies: Fabulous fate of Perrine Martin, To my brother and The case of Ô;.
Selected to draw "the face of France" the Marianne stamp seen on 15 billion [[French Postcards|French stamps]], Ciappa then went on to create his photography exhibition "Imaginary Couples",<ref>(27 January 2013) [http://www.francetvinfo.fr/societe/mariage/mariage-et-homoparentalite/des-celebrites-s-engagent-pour-le-mariage-des-homos_211587.html "Des célébrités s'engagent pour le mariage des homos"]. ''France Télévision Info''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> promoting a positive view of homosexuality.<ref>(22 June 2013) [http://tempsreel.nouvelobs.com/mariage-gay-lesbienne/20130622.OBS4244/l-exposition-d-olivier-ciappa-contre-l-homophobie-vandalisee-a-paris.html "L'exposition d'Olivier Ciappa contre l'homophobie vandalisée à Paris"]. ''Le Nouvel Observateur''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref>

== Works ==

=== Director ===
Ciappa directed stage theatre, two musicals, including Le Cabaret des Hommes Perdus, Winner of best musical and best author at the Molières Awards (French Tony Awards),<ref>(3 August 2012) [https://www.amazon.fr/Cabaret-Hommes-Perdus-Denis-dArcangelo/dp/B000WHBU2S « Le Cabaret des Hommes Perdus"]. ''Amazon''. Retrieved 21 August 2012.</ref> four live action movies, including ''A Mon Frère'' - "In Memory of My Brother".,<ref>(7 August 2010) [http://www.unifrance.org/film/30798/a-mon-frere « A Mon Frère"]. Retrieved 7 August 2010.</ref> Official France entry selection at the 82d Academy Award for Best Live Action Short Film, and one animated short for Disney Animation Studios.<ref>(21 August 2012) [http://disneyandmore.blogspot.com/2012/08/princess-academy-great-animated-short.html « Disney Animated Princess Academy"]. ''Disney and more''. Retrieved 21 August 2012.</ref>

=== Novels ===
In December 2015, the biggest French publishing company [[L'Harmattan]] published his novel "Il Était Deux Frères".<ref>(3 December 2015) [http://www.editions-harmattan.fr/index.asp?navig=catalogue&obj=livre&no=49025'' "Il Était Deux Frères"]. Retrieved 3 December 2015.</ref> Because of the novel's huge success, it quickly became out of stock everywhere.<ref>(3 December 2015) [http://www.placedeslibraires.fr/livre/9782343071404-il-etait-deux-freres-olivier-ciappa/ "Il Était Deux Frères sold out"]. Retrieved 3 December 2015.</ref>

=== Official French president's Marianne ===
Each newly elected President of France is permitted to select an artist to design the "Marianne" (the most common French postage stamp). When newly elected François Hollande indicated he would like to choose Ciappa, a controversy ensued. This honor is usually reserved for more established artists, much later in their careers. [[François Hollande|Hollande]] felt the best way forward was to allow all France's young generation (all of its high school students) to select the artist. As the students made their choice, Ciappa was selected by every high school in the country. His stamp is now known throughout France, and the drawings have been widely displayed including an exhibition at the [[Palais de l'Élysée|French White House]].

=== Fine Art Photography ===

====Imaginary Couples====
During 2012, as the debate over legalizing [[Gay marriage in France|gay marriage]] in France became very polarizing to the French people, Ciappa looked for a way to bring a more positive image of gay love to a homophobic public. His concept was to show loving people – and challenge others to see this love as anything other than the love of two people. The result is an exhibition of black and white photographs, which has seen unprecedented public displays throughout the country, including at the Place de Republique and the [[Hôtel de Ville, Paris|Hotel de Ville]] in Paris. The photographs feature straight people posing as same sex couples, and include leading athletes, film stars and political figures. With that exhibition, Olivier Ciappa became the youngest person to be on the cover of France’s biggest newspaper |Le Figaro]]<ref>(17 July 2013) [http://www.lefigaro.fr/culture/2013/07/17/03004-20130717ARTFIG00310-olivier-ciappa-le-visage-de-la-perseverance.php "Olivier Ciappa, le visage de la persévérance"]. ''Le Figaro''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> A sampling of the photographs are attached below.

Because of the positive impact the exhibition has had throughout France, the [[French President]] and the [[French government]] are taking the exhibition all over the world, from US to Canada, [[Peru]], Brazil.

====International version====
Now, through an arrangement between the Mayor of Los Angeles, the [[Embassy of France, Washington, D.C.|Embassy of France]] and the French Consul General of Los Angeles, "Imaginary Couples" is coming to Los Angeles, where it will be displayed at the Los Angeles Public Library. Ciappa is currently in Los Angeles with the hope of including American athletes and celebrities in the upcoming installations of the exhibition.

====Fait à la main====

During 2014, Olivier Ciappa created : ''"Fait à la main », a new exhibition ephemeral concept only for one night : black&white pictures shown at the exact location it was shot, with the models standing by in the same position. This new pictures shows naked CrossFit champions. After the success of the exhibition, Ciappa created the international worldwide calendar.<ref>(27 January 2014) [http://cfoashop.myshopify.com/products/calendrier-crossfit-original-addicts-by-olivier-ciappa "International Crossfit Calendar"]. ''France Télévision Info''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref>

====Imaginary Couples, the canadian version====

May 2015, Olivier Ciappa creates "Les Couples Imaginaires québecois". Two years before, TV host Monique Giroux discovers the Imaginary Couples exhibition. Seeing the gigantic impact on the french society, she decides to take the exhibition to Montreal and creates new Imaginary Couples in collaboration with TV host Dany Turcotte.<ref>(27 January 2013) [http://www.consulfrance-montreal.org/Monique-Giroux-et-Olivier-Ciappa "Monique Giroux et Olivier Ciappa : deux personnalités, une exposition |auteur"]. ''Consul Général de France''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> She made an association with the French Embassy, IBM and Desjardin bank. Together, they ask Olivier Ciappa to adapt his French exhibition with Canadian celebrities. We can see such personalities as [[Eva Longoria]], [[Véronique Cloutier]], [[Claude Legault]], [[Lara Fabian]], [[Dan Bigras]], [[Etienne Boulay]]<ref>(27 January 2013) [http://www.20minutes.fr/societe/1157429-20130517-journee-lutte-contre-lhomophobie-ma-grosse-peur-cetait-faire-photo-lesbiennes-fasse-fantasmer-heteros "Journée de lutte contre l’homophobie"]. ''Vincent Colas''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref>

.<ref>(27 January 2013) [http://www.fugues.com/238648-article-y-a-de-lamour-dans-lair.html « Exposition canadienne"]. ''Fugues''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> December 2013, Olivier Ciappa goes to Montreal to take pictures of their biggest singers, actors, politicians and TV hosts. It will take the French Consul a year and a half to create the biggest exhibition ever attended in Montreal.<ref>(27 January 2013) [http://www.consulfrance-montreal.org/Les-Allies-s-exposent « Les Alliés s’exposent"]. ''Consul Général de France''. Retrieved 28 April 2015.</ref> During the shooting, celebrities started to tweet making of pictures and parts of the final work. Due to the success of their posts, it was decided that all pictures would be removed and no interview would be given until the exhibition.<ref>(28 April 2015) [http://hollywoodpq.com/2013/12/13/penelope-mcquade-et-anne-marie-cadieux-dans-une-campagne-contre-lhomophobie "Campagne contre l'homophobie"]. ''Hollywoodpq''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> It was then decided that there would be two exhibitions : a public one at the [[Complexe Desjardins]], the biggest place in Montreal. And a more elitist exhibition, at the Montreal Museum of Art.<ref>(28 April 2015) [http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1534333/desjardins-group-presents-allies-in-the-spotlight-at-complexe-desjardins-and-the-montreal-museum-of-fine-arts "Présentation par le groupe Desjardin"]. ''Banque Desjardins''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> Just before the exhibition, le Huffington Post reveals that no sport champion accepted to be part of the exhibition because of sport’s homophobia<ref>(28 April 2015) [http://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2015/05/06/les-grands-noms-du-quebec-forment-des-couples-homosexuels-imaginaires_n_7227688.html "Des célébrités s'engagent pour le mariage des homos"]. ''Interview Radio Canada''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> The information became big in newspapers and Olivier Ciappa send a radio message to ask sports champions to change their mind.<ref>(28 April 2015) [http://ici.radio-canada.ca/emissions/medium_large/2014-2015/chronique.asp?idchronique=372513 « Etienne Boulay à Radio Canada"]. ‘'ITV Radio Canada''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref> Few hours later, football champion [[Etienne Boulay]] calls Radio Canada and accepts the photoshoot. He then came to Radio Canada to explain his change of mind after viewing the peaceful images of the exhibition.<ref>(28 April 2015) [http://ici.radio-canada.ca/emissions/medium_large/2011-2012/chronique.asp?idChronique=372839 "Des célébrités s'engagent pour le mariage des homos"]. ''Interview Radio Canada''. Retrieved 28 April 2015.</ref>

====The Montreal Museum of Art : Tombé dans l’Oeil====

Le Musée des Beaux Arts de Montréal presents in 2015 a new kind of exhibition were the old museum masterpieces would be put together to create Imaginary Couples. With eadphones, the people coming to the museum would hear imaginary stories between the characters of the paintings.<ref>(28 April 2015) [https://www.bloomberg.com/research/markets/news/article.asp?docKey=600-201505111144CANADANWCANADAPR_C5134-1 "Des célébrités s'engagent pour le mariage des homos"]. ‘'Press release The Montreal museum of art''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref>

====Quebec City : La Photo qui parle====

In September 2015, Quebec City presents a new version of the Imaginary Couples Exhibition. All visitors heard interviews of the artist and the models while they were discovering the pictures in the exhibition. Videos were adding to the presentation with making of images .<ref>(3 April 2015) [http://www.fugues.com/243495-article-une-partie-de-lexpo-les-couples-imaginaires-presentee-a-quebec.html]. ‘'Quebec City exhibition''. Retrieved 28 April 2014.</ref>

